Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of China-U.S. relations unsettled large parts of Asia.
A year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly grand "state visit plus" to Beijing, from which China had hoped that Trump's anti-China campaign rhetoric would finally become a thing of the past.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the U.S. "strategic engagement" with China with "strategic competition."
In addition, the U.S., European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is significant uncertainty in the financial markets, growth is slowing down in China and Europe, and in America, higher interest rates are beginning to take effect.
Uncertainty regarding the future development of nuclear negotiations with North Korea also clouds the picture.
What are the prospects for the relationship between the USA and China in 2019?
It is likely that an agreement on the reduction of the bilateral trade deficit and on China's import decisions in this regard will be reached by March.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the targeted timeframe.
If each tariff were negotiated one by one, it could take a year.
Should Chinese economic reformers, however, adopt a more drastic approach by gradually committing to the abolition of all tariffs and urging Americans to do the same, a faster result could be achieved.
This, however, would run counter to the practices of Chinese trade officials, who have been trained for decades to give little, let alone everything at once.
The reform of the so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nevertheless, a reform is something different from the way contractual agreements might be interpreted in practice, even if there were no specific provisions regarding technology transfer.
However, the protection of intellectual property is extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made under the government of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
However, their enforcement or legal action against violations of intellectual property rights remains a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism involves subjecting relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international commercial arbitration institutions based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing the protection of intellectual property rights.
Should China raise objections, it could develop its own international trade arbitration process based in China.
To do so, however, it would have to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel in order to strengthen its international credibility.
Nobody has trust in Chinese commercial courts.
For its own internal reform needs, China must move toward entirely independent commercial and civil chambers within its judicial system, even though the criminal chamber continues to be subject to political control.
American concerns regarding state subsidies within the framework of the country's "Made in China 2025" strategy will be difficult to resolve.
The fact is that all countries provide some level of state support to their domestic technology industries, although this is highest in China.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, the compliance would be difficult to assess.
I am not confident that a negotiation result will be achieved in this area.
Perhaps America simply needs to outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China offers tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
Thus, China could decide over time to take the drastic step of agreeing to duty-free access not only with the United States, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
In this way, China would have an almost irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and to counter the trend toward protectionism.
As part of such a shift, China could request the member states of the Trans-Pacific Partnership (TPP) to join, in order to surpass the United States (which withdrew from the free trade agreement as one of the first actions taken by Trump) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can remarkably be nimble when it detects a political breach and market opening.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since the recent visit of Prime Minister Shinzo Abe to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the United States, China is likely to strive in its general foreign and security policy in 2019 to reduce conflicts in its relations with other countries.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a significant decrease in Chinese incursions into the area of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China also aims to ease tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) over the South China Sea by accelerating negotiations on a "Code of Conduct."
Moreover, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India following the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China could begin to moderate its stance toward Taiwan, given the electoral setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party, which supports independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would, of course, change radically if the USA continues with further significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the USA in the South China Sea continue to occur, and the conflict could escalate if the USA more forcefully reaffirm their stance on "freedom of navigation" next year.
Throughout all of Eurasia, China will continue to implement its major project, the "New Silk Road."
In recent months, however, the initiative has caused less political controversy in China.
Among Chinese officials, there are already discussions about revising certain modalities, following negative reactions caused by Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China and concerns regarding the long-term financiability of the New Silk Road.
Therefore, triumphal reports about the New Silk Road may be heard less frequently in 2019.
Furthermore, China is likely to consolidate and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than highlighting new institutions of international political action.
It will likely continue to appear as a new advocate for the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More prudent representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on the existing mechanisms of the global rules-based system, especially when the United States consistently shows contempt for it.
While China attempts to stabilize its relations with the United States and ease tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will likely use the year 2019 to form a well-founded assessment of the future of U.S. policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his administration, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new U.S. strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that America's stance toward China has undergone a fundamental change, they are still uncertain about the exact nature of this change and whether a fundamental strategic shift (as opposed to tactical measures) is warranted.
